2026-04-21 01:35:26 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control module 3 switch contacts / internal series path', 'Interconnection between control module 2 output pair and control module 3 input pair'] hypothesis_explanation='With the new battery, we have a solid 12 V at the PSU and across control module 1 and 2: PSU output, control 1 input/output, and control 2 input/output all show ~12 V between their (+) and (−) conductors. From control output cables (+/−) 3 onward, both conductors sit near 0 V and no polarity inversion was found.\n\nIn this system the two conductors are continuous from PSU (+/−) through every control module to the load. If 12 V is still present on the output pair of the second control module but has vanished on the next pair in the chain, the only ways this can occur are:\n1) An internal open in control module 3’s series path (e.g., failed or miswired switch contacts, broken track, etc.), or\n2) An open/miswired interconnection between control module 2’s output pair and control module 3’s input pair.\n\nEither of these faults would leave the downstream side floating; with all other modules and the load off, both downstream conductors will sit at a near-zero potential with respect to ground, exactly as observed. Upstream modules and their LEDs remain dark because, although 12 V exists at their connectors, their own LED branches may not be powered under this fault condition, and the main problem clearly localizes to the segment between control module 2’s output and control module 3’s input.\n\nThus the remaining root cause is confined to control module 3’s internal series path or its immediate interconnection to the output of control module 2, which should be repaired/replaced accordingly.'
